h redshifts\nclose to that of NGC 4709.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 30 Nov 1998 13:07:22 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 19 Jan 2000 16:19:17 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 2 Feb 2000 10:48:07 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-10-31"}
{"id":"astro-ph/9811454","submitter":"Mike Turner","authors":"Michael S. Turner (U. Chicago and Fermilab)","title":"Dark Matter and Dark Energy in the Universe","comments":"22 pages LaTeX with 7 eps figures. To be published in The Third\n  Stromlo Symposium: The Galactic Halo, eds. B.K. Gibson, T.S. Axelrod, and\n  M.E. Putnam (Astron. Soc. Pac. Conf. Series, Vol. 666, 1999)","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph hep-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  For the first time, we have a plausible, complete accounting of matter and\nenergy in the Universe. Expressed a fraction of the critical density it goes\nlike this: neutrinos, between 0.3% and 15%; stars, 0.5%; baryons (total), 5%;\nmatter (total), 40%; smooth, dark energy, 60%; adding up to the critical\ndensity. This accounting is consistent with the inflationary prediction of a\nflat Universe and defines three dark-matter problems: Where are the dark\nbaryons? What is the nonbaryonic dark matter? What is the nature of the dark\nenergy? The leading candidate for the (optically) dark baryons is diffuse hot\ngas; the leading candidates for the nonbaryonic dark matter are slowly moving\nelementary particles left over from the earliest moments (cold dark matter),\nsuch as axions or neutralinos; the leading candidates for the dark energy\ninvolve fundamental physics and include a cosmological constant (vacuum\nenergy), a rolling scalar field (quintessence), and light, frustrated\ntopological defects.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 29 Nov 1998 17:23:50 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
